ung’s highly original study situates later Realism for the first time within the larger social, political, and economic framework and argues for its centrality in understanding the development of modern art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArtxPolitical aspects. 0aImpressionism (Art). 0aPainting, Frenchy19th century. 0aRealism in art. 0aTime in art. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh1 aBastien-Lepage, Jules, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaillebotte, Gustave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnsor, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaffaëlli, Jean- François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoll, Alfred- Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030020832040uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021285340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300212853423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300212853/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY